---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/baseLayout.astro";
import NavMain from "@/components/navMain.astro";
import "../../styles/components/expandCollapseAccordion.css";
---

<script type="module" src="/scripts/components/expandCollapseAccordion.js"></script>

<BaseLayout>
<NavMain 
  title="Expand/Collapse Accordion"
  navCenterText="Expand/Collapse Accordion"
  htmlLinkHref="https://github.com/jaretpeerson/toggle/blob/main/src/pages/components/expandCollapseAccordion.astro"
  cssLinkHref="https://github.com/jaretpeerson/toggle/blob/main/src/styles/components/expandCollapseAccordion.css"
  javascriptLinkHref="https://github.com/jaretpeerson/toggle/blob/main/public/scripts/components/expandCollapseAccordion.js" />


  <div class="container">
    <div class="accordian-container">

      <div class="cards-container">

        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header">
            <span>CSS-First</span>
            <div class="plus-icon active">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                <path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M11 4H13V6V11H20V13H13V18V20H11V18V13H4V11H11V6V4Z" fill="currentColor"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body show">
            JavaScript handles logic. CSS handles expression. When something needs to open, close, or animate, JavaScript toggles a class. CSS already knows what that class looks like and how to get there. This separation keeps components readable, portable, and easy to adjust.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header">
            <span>Production-Ready</span>
            <div class="plus-icon">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                <path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M11 4H13V6V11H20V13H13V18V20H11V18V13H4V11H11V6V4Z" fill="currentColor"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            Every component runs out of the box. Copy the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript and it works. No dependencies to install. No libraries that break on update. Framework-agnostic code you can adapt and ship as your own.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-header">
            <span>Lightweight</span>
            <div class="plus-icon">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                <path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M11 4H13V6V11H20V13H13V18V20H11V18V13H4V11H11V6V4Z" fill="currentColor"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-body">
            CSS transitions run on the GPU and stay smooth even when JavaScript is busy. Components built this way are faster, easier to maintain, and fundamentally more resilient. When JavaScript fails to load, styles still apply and the experience degrades instead of breaking.
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
  

</BaseLayout>